{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4f6fc373-33e6-49c4-bf3f-06338f8e72fc","content":"## What happened\n\nMicrosoft removed the built-in **DSA implementation on macOS** (and iOS/tvOS). Apple deprecated DSA in their Security framework, and .NET relied on Apple's native crypto libraries for DSA on that platform. After the removal, `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS. Linux and Windows are unaffected because they use OpenSSL and CNG respectively, which still support DSA.\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Option 1 – Migrate away from DSA (recommended)**\nDSA is a legacy algorithm with limited key sizes. If you control both signing and verification, switch to **ECDSA** or **RSA**.\n\n**Option 2 – Use BouncyCastle for legacy verification**\nIf you must verify existing DSA signatures, use a managed implementation that doesn't depend on platform crypto:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(\n    byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] data, byte[] signature)\n{\n    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)\n        PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\n\n    var signer = new DsaSigner();\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);\n\n    // Decode the DER-encoded signature into (r, s)\n    var derSeq = (Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Sequence)\n        Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Object.FromByteArray(signature);\n    var r = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)derSeq[0]).Value;\n    var s = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)derSeq[1]).Value;\n\n    // Hash the data with SHA-1 (or whatever hash your legacy sigs use)\n    var digest = DigestUtilities.CalculateDigest(\"SHA-1\", data);\n\n    return signer.VerifySignature(digest, r, s);\n}\n```\n\nThis is a fully managed implementation—works identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS regardless of platform crypto support.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"928b1ebd-cf09-46ef-a595-4935fa389a4e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nIn .NET, the `DSA` class on macOS historically used Apple's Security framework (SecKey APIs) or OpenSSL. Microsoft has been deprecating older cryptographic algorithms over time.\n\nStarting with .NET 7+, Microsoft began marking DSA as obsolete on certain platforms. The key change is that **in .NET 9, DSA on macOS was already limited**, and Microsoft has been progressively removing support for DSA on macOS because Apple's CommonCrypto/Security framework doesn't natively support DSA well.\n\n\nThe real issue is that starting in .NET 9, `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS since Microsoft removed the macOS DSA implementation after Apple deprecated it in their security frameworks. Looking at the Microsoft documentation for .NET 9, DSA support was indeed removed on macOS, iOS, and tvOS. But the user mentioned it's working on .NET 10 in April 2026, which doesn't align with that timeline—either this is a preview scenario or the breaking change happened at a different version than I initially thought. Let me reconsider what I actually know: DSA was marked obsolete in .NET 7, but the actual `PlatformNotSupportedException` on Apple platforms came later, and I'm not entirely certain which version introduced it.\n\nRegardless of the exact version numbers, the core issue is clear—Microsoft removed DSA support on macOS because Apple deprecated it in their cryptographic frameworks. The solution is straightforward: either migrate to RSA or ECDSA, or use a cross-platform library like BouncyCastle if legacy DSA signature verification is absolutely necessary.","outputTokens":1637,"requestId":"CFC0:28DE61:197F5B8:1CE6552:69E821A1"},"id":"80245a10-419c-43a5-bb60-640773d147c3","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:17:55.361Z","parentId":"7d776f81-c493-4db9-b39b-a79626fa0e29"}
